## 11. Key Findings & Inferences

### 11.1 Coordination Collapse Is Model-Family Independent
The Qwen 3B model achieves a **0.83 Pass@1 as a single agent** — far stronger than DeepSeek 1.3B (0.65). Yet both collapse to nearly identical 2-Agent performance (~0.41). This definitively shows coordination collapse is a property of the **pipeline architecture**, not the model.

### 11.2 The Architect Is the Bottleneck
- 100% of collapsed cases had defective specs (primarily empty FUNCTION SIGNATURE sections)
- The Architect consistently drops the **original function name** — creating a valid implementation with a *different* function name than expected by HumanEval's test harness
- This is not a model capacity issue; it's an information-theoretic lossy compression issue inherent in natural language spec intermediation

### 11.3 The Validator Has a Detection-Remediation Gap
- Detection works well: the structural pre-check catches 76/77 violations
- Remediation largely fails: only 21/77 triggered cases recovered, because the **revision still uses the same defective spec**
- The LLM Validator itself was nearly redundant (caught only 1 case the structural check missed)

### 11.4 Difficulty Amplifies Collapse
- Easy tasks: 3-Agent achieves 0.78 (near-full recovery)
- Medium tasks: drops to 0.40 (high collapse persists)
- Hard tasks: drops to 0.39 (essentially no benefit from the pipeline)

### 11.5 Scaling Does Not Fix Collapse
Per the cross-family comparison, scaling from 1.3B to 6.7B (DeepSeek) did not reduce collapse. The Qwen 3B ablation further confirms this — a stronger baseline model (0.83 vs 0.65) still collapses to the same level.

